  <text>
      <body>
         <entry xml:id="agomen-dlgenr"
            xml:lang="en"
            type="mainEntry"
            prev="#"
            next="#"
            source="Genesis Rabbah">
            <form type="lemma" opt="false">
               <orth type="lemma" xml:lang="jpa" opt="false" select="true">אגומין</orth>
               <orth type="transliteration" xml:lang="fjb" opt="false">ʾgwmyn</orth>
               <pron notation="rabbinic" opt="false">ʾagomen</pron>
               <gramGrp opt="false">
                  <gram type="pos" opt="false">verb</gram>
               </gramGrp>
               <form type="variant">
                  <orth type="variant" xml:lang="jpa">אגימין</orth>
                  <orth type="transliteration" xml:lang="fjb">ʾgymyn</orth>
                  <pron notation="rabbinic">ʾagemen</pron>
               </form>
            </form>
            <sense xml:id="agomen-dlgenr-1">
               <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en" subtype="sense">
                  <quote>let us go!</quote>
               </cit>
               <cit type="translationEquivalent" xml:lang="grc">
                  <quote>ἄγωμεν</quote>
               </cit>
               <cit type="example" xml:lang="jpa">
                  <quote>אמר ר' לוי ארי כעס על הבהמה ועל החיה, אמרין מאן אזיל מפייס יתיה, אמר תעלא אנא ידע לו ש' מתלין ואנא מפייס יתיה, אמרין 
                  <app>
                     <lem>אגימין</lem>
                     <rdg wit="#Vat1">אגו מן</rdg>
                     <rdg wit="#Ox1 Vat2 K">אגומי</rdg>
                     <rdg wit="#V">אגומין</rdg>
                     <rdg wit="#Ox2">איגומי</rdg>
                  </app></quote>
                  <bibl>
                     <ref type="witness">78,7</ref>
                     <ref type="witness">II 925: 1</ref>
                  </bibl>
                  <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                     <quote>R. Levi said: A lion was angry with the cattle and the beasts. They said: “Who will go to appease him?” Said the fox: “I know three hundred fables and I will appease him.” They said: “Let us go!”</quote>
                  </cit>
                  <note>= <bibl type="ancient">Yalq 133 [II 668: 44]</bibl>: (<term xml:lang="jpa">אגומין</term>)</note>
               </cit>
            </sense>
            <note><bibl type="modern">AC I 23ab</bibl>: <term xml:lang="jpa">אגומין</term> <term xml:lang="fjb">ʾgwmyn</term> <term xml:lang="rabbinic">ʾagumen</term>. Cf. also <bibl type="modern">Levy I 21b</bibl>; <bibl type="modern">Krauss, LW I 152</bibl>; <bibl type="modern">Krauss, LW II 8b</bibl>; MY ad. loc.; <bibl type="modern">Jastrow I 11b</bibl>; <bibl type="modern">Sokoloff, DJPA 5a</bibl>. <bibl type="modern">Bauer (1988) 26</bibl> attests it as a rabb. loanword. Sokoloff regards the etymology as unclear. MY / AC I 23ab suggest also: Gr. <term xml:lang="grc">ἄγε μὴν</term> (cf. Vat 1) „well then!“, „let it be so!” (cf. Freedman / Simon II 720). Hapax in rabb. lit.</note>
            <ref type="bibliography">
               <bibl>
                  <title>Krauss, LW</title>
                  <citedRange>8b</citedRange>
               </bibl>
            </ref>
         </entry>
      </body>
